Rephrased Question:

A city uses an average of 4.0 million gallons per day for its daily water needs, and it also must meet a fire flow demand of 4.32 million gallons per day sustained over 3 hours. The water is delivered directly from a pumping station located 40,000 ft from the center of the service area. The hydraulic system is approximated by an equivalent pipe of 24 inches in diameter with a Hazen-Williams roughness coefficient of C = 120. Determine the necessary hydraulic heads at the pumping station under the following conditions:

a) When there is no storage tank in the system.

b) When an elevated storage tank is installed 5,000 ft upstream of the demand center (i.e., 35,000 ft from the pumping station).

c) When an elevated storage tank is installed 5,000 ft downstream of the demand center (i.e., 45,000 ft from the pumping station).

a) \boxed{\text{No storage tank scenario}}  
b) \boxed{\text{Elevated tank located 5,000 ft upstream from the demand center}}  
c) \boxed{\text{Elevated tank located 5,000 ft downstream from the demand center}}

We can rephrase the query as follows:

A pump is supplying water at a head of 130 ft and an operating temperature of 100°F. The surrounding atmospheric pressure is 14.3 psi absolute. At the pump’s inlet, the pressure is reduced by 17 inches of mercury (i.e., it is 17 in. Hg below atmospheric pressure), and the water flows at 12 ft/sec. Determine the available NPSH and the corresponding cavitation parameter. (Hint: The head for water is obtained by multiplying the mercury head by the specific gravity of mercury.)

\boxed{\text{final_answer}}

question:
The movement on the surface beneath a cyclone is characterized by the streamfunction and velocity potential given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \psi(x, y)=\Psi\left[1-e^{-\frac{\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)}{L^{2}}}\right] \\
& \chi(x, y)=X e^{-\frac{\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)}{L^{2}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\Psi$ and $X$ are constants. Calculate (a) the horizontal velocity, (b) the horizontal divergence, and (c) the vertical vorticity.
